# DrugOS Caddyfile
#
# ROOT FIX for FE-007 (open SSRF proxy via ?XTransformPort=).
#
# Previously: the :81 site had a `reverse_proxy localhost:{query.XTransformPort}`
# block that let ANY external caller make Caddy open a TCP connection to
# arbitrary internal ports on the host. This is a textbook open SSRF
# proxy. With it, an attacker could:
#   - Reach cloud-metadata endpoints (169.254.169.254) to steal IAM creds
#   - Port-scan the internal network
#   - Reach unauthenticated admin endpoints on localhost
#   - Pivot through the host to other services on the VPC
#
# ROOT FIX: the entire `XTransformPort` handler is GONE. There is no
# legitimate reason for an external HTTP request to dictate which internal
# port Caddy proxies to. If you need to expose multiple internal services,
# define one Caddy site per service with a hardcoded reverse_proxy target.
#
# If you genuinely need dynamic port routing (e.g., for a multi-tenant
# preview environment), implement it with:
#   - An explicit allowlist of allowed ports, AND
#   - Authenticated requests (mTLS or a signed header), AND
#   - A loopback-only listener that is never exposed to the internet.
# Do NOT put the dynamic logic in the public Caddyfile.

